the actions which they brought for the establishment of their claims, and by whom the assets were sold in lots; the proceeds of the sale were distributed by the judge among the creditors, in a determinate order of priority (for which see Poste's Gaius p. 3 52). Properry which the insol- vent might subsequently acquire remained liable to successive sales, until the creditors had been paid in full.

Embarrassed debtors could also usually avail themselves of a pro· cedure more in the nature of a voluntary composition with creditors, called cessio bonorum (Blc iii. 25. 8; iv. 6. 40; ib. ¹4 4 inf), which was introduced by a lex Iulia of one of the two first Caesars. By adopting this course they escaped liability ro arrest and imprisonment, Cod. 7. 71. r, which bankrupts proper might still incur if the missio in bona produced uo results; a debtor could be committed to prison ar the outset only on the applicarion of the Treasury. Further, they did not become infames, like banlerupts, Cod. 2. 12. 2, and were allowed to retain so much of their after-acquired property as was necessary for their subsistence (beneficium competentiae, see on Bk. iv. 6. 37 inf), Dig. 42. 3. 4, cod 7. 7¹· r. No debtor‚ however, could claim ro make a cessio bonorum whose insol· vency was due to his own fault, Cod. 7. 71. 8. pr.
